  "id": "019d419f-4007-7c93-ae90-577c77a0c61a",
  "content": "# Agentic Retrieval Protocol -- Decision Record (2026-03-31)\n\n## What: Server-side intelligence for agent-corvia interactions (issue #47)\n\nImplemented all five design areas of the agentic retrieval protocol:\n1. Quality signals in corvia_search responses (confidence, suggestion, gap_detected)\n2. Context injection via max_tokens + compact format on corvia_context\n3. Knowledge gap detection from low-confidence search signals (dashboard endpoint)\n4. Foundation for retrieval feedback loops (extends #12 access tracking)\n5. Write deduplication (cosine > 0.90 blocks, 0.80-0.90 warns, force_write bypasses)\n\n## Key Design Decisions:\n1. Quality signals computed on pre-filter results (not post min_score) to reflect true retrieval health.\n2. Suggestion generation is template-based, zero latency cost (not LLM-generated).\n3. Gap detection uses text-prefix normalization for topic grouping (semantic clustering deferred).\n4. Compact augmenter uses break (not continue) since results are relevance-ranked.\n5. Write dedup returns structured JSON with isError:true for Blocked responses.\n6. Format parameter validated server-side. min_score clamped [0.0, 1.0]. max_tokens clamped [100, 4000].\n\n## Review Findings Worth Remembering:\n- Always compute quality signals before client-side filtering to avoid false gap signals.\n- In relevance-ranked results, break on budget overflow rather than continue-and-skip.\n- MCP isError field should be used for rejected operations (not just plain text messages).\n- Response shapes across format modes should share a consistent base schema.\n\n## What Blocked / Surprised:\n- Gap detector topic grouping with 4-word prefix was too fine-grained, reduced to 3 words.\n- Compact mode needed 2x retrieval budget to avoid premature truncation by the default augmenter.\n- Five reviewers independently identified quality signal on post-filtered results as the top issue.",
